05114nam a22007695i 9781501763052DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021040307  a97815017630527 a10.1515/97815017630522doi  a(DE-B1597)602082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJZ1314b.H46 2022 7aPOL0110102bisacsh1 aHenry, Iain D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReliability and Alliance Interdependence :bThe United States and Its Allies in Asia, 1949–1969 /cIain D. Henry. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (258 p.) :b2 maps, 2 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Alliances, Reliability, and Interdependence -- t2. Forming Alliances in Asia, 1949–1951 -- t3. Unleashing and Releashing Chiang Kai-shek, 1953–1954 -- t4. Allies Encourage Limits on US Loyalty to Formosa, 1954–1955 -- t5. Revision of the US-Japan Alliance, 1955–1960 -- t6. Negotiating the Reversion of Okinawa, 1967–1969 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Reliability and Alliance Interdependence, Iain D. Henry argues for a more sophisticated approach to alliance politics and ideas of interdependence. It is often assumed that if the United States failed to defend an ally, then this disloyalty would instantly and irrevocably damage US alliances across the globe. Henry proposes that such damage is by no means inevitable, and that predictions of disaster are dangerously simplistic. If other allies fear the risks of military escalation more than the consequences of the United States abandoning an ally, then they will welcome, encourage, and even praise such an instance of disloyalty. It is also often assumed that alliance interdependence only constrains US policy options, but Henry shows how the US can manipulate interdependence to set an example of what constitutes acceptable allied behavior. Henry tests this theory of alliance interdependence using case studies drawn from Asia during the first half of the Cold War. Using declassified documents, he explores five case studies involving US alliances with South Korea, Japan, the Republic of China, the Philippines, Australia, and New Zealand. Reliability and Alliance Interdependence makes a substantial contribution to our understanding of how America's alliances in Asia function as an interdependent system.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAlliancesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aalliance loyalty, alliance politics, US strategy in asia, US foreign policy, US alliances, alliance reliability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176305240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501763052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501763052/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-